  "doc_id": "33537",
  "text": "Mutants of Skp1 are known to exhibit defective phenotypes in the cell cycle control. The skp1-a7 temperature-sensitive mutant arrests in G2 phase of the mitotic cell cycle due to activation of the Rad3-dependent DNA damage checkpoint [CITATION_1] . The rad3D skp1-a7 double mutant suppressed the G2 arrest at the high temperature. This indicates that the DNA damage checkpoint is ectopically activated in the skp1-a7 mutant [CITATION_2] . Interestingly, the skp1-a7 mutant exhibits abnormally-bent spindles and fails in nuclear division at anaphase [CITATION_3] . This implies that Skp1 may regulate organization of spindle microtubules and/or elasticity of the nuclear envelope. The rad3D skp1-a7 double mutant, however, no longer shows the bent-spindle phenotype in anaphase [CITATION_4] . The F-box protein responsible for this bent-spindle phenotype has not been identified.",
